                    "get_subject_filter": "Graduate Fine Arts",
                    "get_acad_level_filter": "Graduate",
                    "get_course_number_filter": "6020",
                    "get_section_description_filter": "<span>What is appropriation? Is it cultural violation? Is it an effective strategy for cultural critique? Is it an ethically neutral reality of cultural history and creative process? Is it an act of love? Is it shallow? Is it rich? Is it a way of claiming kinship or belonging? Yes, and when is what true? Who gets to decide? This course dives in to questions about owning culture. We&#39;ll look at art (mostly 20th and 21st century US painting and performance) and read art criticism, anthropology and archeology, contemporary journalism, artists&#39; statements, etc to get a feel for the different ways people understand what it means to use other people&#39;s work, images, and lives.</span><span>\u00a0</span><span>Most of us have been taught the &#34;right&#34; and &#34;wrong&#34; answers to many of the questions that arise in this course. Repeating these is neither critically helpful nor particularly interesting. Our emphasis, therefore, will be on asking better questions, and building a collective conversation in which it&#39;s okay to test out ideas without coming to final conclusions. In addition to designing and leading one class conversation, you will bring our theory into your practice through several making assignments-- creative acts of love, criticism, and theft.</span>",
